<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[Overkill]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-04-01T21:46:53-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-04-01T21:46:53-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12224&amp;p=144253#p144253</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12224&amp;p=144253#p144253"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Can Everdrive-GB run homebrew?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12224&amp;p=144253#p144253"><![CDATA[
If you need to reset the Game Boy CPU of the Super Game Boy from software, it should be possible.<br /><br />You could run code uploaded to the SNES RAM via SGB commands: <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">DATA_TRN</tt>/<tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">DATA_SND</tt> (<tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">DATA_SND</tt> is more efficient for small transfers, since you don't need to setup VRAM to send the message, you just use the joypad port), then <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">JUMP</tt>. You'd need a short 65816 routine to clear bit 7 of <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$6003</tt> (according to <a href="http://www.dforce3000.de/pub/d4s_super_gameboy_notes.pdf" class="postlink">http://www.dforce3000.de/pub/d4s_super_gameboy_notes.pdf</a>). This would reset the GB side, and then you would need to <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">JMP</tt> to the reset vector SNES-side to allow recovering from the SGB <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">JUMP</tt> command.<br /><br />Actually, I wonder if the reset handler of the Super Game Boy already causes a GB CPU reset on startup? Then your routine could just <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">JMP &#40;$FFFC&#41;</tt> and skip the <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">$6003</tt> writes altogether.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4803">Overkill</a> — Wed Apr 01, 2015 9:46 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
</entry>
